User survey for ImagingSociety 2025 - National MRI research infrastructure in Norway

Author

Dr. Athanasia M. Mowinckel

Published

October 8, 2025

Background

This report presents an analysis of the survey data collected for the national grant scheme application for MRI research infrastructure in Norway. The survey was designed to gather insights from the research community on the current use, needs, and challenges related to MRI for human research.

The following sections will present a summary of the key findings, including graphical representations of the quantitative data and a textual summary of the open-ended responses, with the help of the Gemini LMM.

Survey Results

Of the 65 responses, 29 participants reported they currently use MRI for research, 45% indicate a future interest in using the new MRI facility for their work.

Participant Demographics

This section provides an overview of the survey participants’ roles and institutions.

Research Areas

The survey respondents represent a diverse range of research areas, with a strong emphasis on cognitive neuroscience and neurology. Key areas of focus include:

  • Cognitive Neuroscience: This is a dominant theme, covering attention, decision-making, language, music, predictive processing, and general cognitive function.
  • Neurology: Includes research on neurodegenerative diseases (Alzheimer’s, dementia, Parkinson’s), Multiple Sclerosis, stroke, brain tumors, and epilepsy.
  • Mental Health: Encompasses research on mental disorders, psychotherapy, child and adolescent psychiatry, mood disorders, psychosis, anorexia nervosa, and brain development related to mental health.
  • Aging: Research focuses on healthy aging, dementia, menopause and aging cognition, cerebrovascular disease, and related conditions.
  • Brain Imaging: Many respondents utilize various brain imaging techniques (MRI, fNIRS, EEG) for research, including methods development in MRI.
  • Other Notable Areas: Research also covers sexual health, brain injury (including sports-related), women’s health, pain (neurobiology of pain), speech and language processing, immunology/metabolism/epigenetics and more.

In summary, the survey captures a wide range of neuroscience and related research fields with significant concentration in cognitive neuroscience, neurology and mental health related fields and the use of brain imaging technologies.

How MRI Would Enhance Research

Based on the survey responses, increased and improved access to MRI would significantly expand and improve research in several key areas:

  • Expanded Research Scope & New Avenues: Researchers would be able to explore new research questions, areas like sexual dysfunction, the neurobiological bases of bilingualism, pain mechanisms, cognitive processes, and the impact of interventions on brain structure and function. It would also enable researchers to conduct studies on previously inaccessible populations or conditions (e.g., those in Northern Norway or those with Cerebral Visual Impairments). Some are currently shifting away from areas because of lack of access.

  • Improved Study Design & Statistical Power: Reliable access would enable researchers to plan and conduct well-powered studies with larger sample sizes, longitudinal studies, and multi-center collaborations, increasing the robustness and generalizability of findings.

  • Enhanced Methodological Capabilities: Researchers would be able to implement advanced MRI techniques (e.g., fMRI, DTI, resting-state fMRI, 7T MRI) and develop novel MRI sequences.

  • Bridging Research Gaps: MRI would help integrate different levels of research, linking behavior, genetics, and brain activity. It would also bridge the gap between pre-clinical findings (e.g., in vitro or computational models) and in vivo human brain function.

  • Clinical Translation & Personalized Medicine: MRI would contribute to the identification of biomarkers for various disorders (e.g., ADHD in women), inform more accurate diagnostics, personalize treatment approaches, and monitor disease progression (e.g., in multiple sclerosis, lupus nephritis).

  • Career Advancement & Funding Opportunities: Access to MRI would allow researchers to gain experience, collect pilot data, and publish neuroimaging studies, significantly increasing their chances of securing research funding.

  • For some, MRI is a basic fundamental need, even crucial, or the basis of their research.

  • Unmet needs for clinical trial implementation, and early detection of changes in tissues.

Key barriers to improved research include: high costs, limited scanner availability, lack of dedicated research support, and inflexible scheduling. Researchers desire easier, cheaper, and more flexible access, as well as the ability to develop their own sequences and collaborate across sites.

Future Needs

This section analyzes which conditions are considered most important for the future of MRI research in Norway.

Summary of Free-text Comments

This section provides a summary of the open-ended comments, generated using the Gemini LMM.

These responses emphasize the need for enhanced MRI research infrastructure and accessibility in Norway. A key theme is the desire for increased research-focused access, potentially through a dedicated research scanner located outside of the clinical environment, closer to university campuses, and with prioritized research time and potentially more favorable pricing. Building a collaborative, nationwide MRI research community, similar to the UK Biobank model with synchronized scanners across population centers, is seen as crucial for large-scale population mapping and advancing brain science. Standardized capabilities across different MRI sites are desired, alongside consistent and routinely available research hours. Finally, the ambition of having a 7T scanner for subcortical research is also highlighted.

Conclusion

This survey provides compelling evidence for a significant unmet need for research-dedicated MRI scanners in Norway. The responses clearly indicate that researchers across various institutions and disciplines, from universities to hospitals, are facing challenges related to access, cost, and scanner capabilities. These limitations directly impede the progress of cutting-edge research across fields like neuroscience, psychology, and medicine.

The desire for increased scanning capacity, advanced imaging technologies, and dedicated research support staff highlights a critical bottleneck in the Norwegian research landscape. Addressing this need through strategic investment in research-focused MRI infrastructure would not only empower Norwegian researchers to conduct more innovative and impactful studies but also foster greater collaboration, attract international talent, and ultimately improve healthcare outcomes for the Norwegian population. The time to act is now to ensure Norway remains competitive and at the forefront of global MRI research.
